Dear members of the mailing list

	Dublin Core in Multiple Languages (dc-international@cs.ait.ac.th):


This list has been quiet lately, but I have seen almost all of you
face to face over the past few weeks -- in Helsinki (at DC5), Osnabrueck
(the German metadata workshop), Tsukuba (ISDL97), or in Bangkok
(Laszlo Kovacs was here).

What has emerged is a plan to link versions of DC-Simple in different
languages -- just the fifteen basic elements -- into a simple distributed
registry.  This registry would use a Resource Description Framework
capability to _inherit_ the fifteen machine-readable indexing tokens (like
"DC.Creator") from a central source and _override_ human-readable text
locally with labels and descriptions in Thai, Japanese, and Portuguese
(see http://www.cs.ait.ac.th/~tbaker/registry.gif).  Most browsers are not
normally configured for Japanese and Thai, so we may use a multilingual
browser applet developed at the University of Library and Information
Science in Tsukuba for displaying the proper fonts on browsers enabled
for Java (see http://mhtml.ulis.ac.jp).

Aside from English and Thai, this simple registry could include Japanese
(Shigeo Sugimoto), German (Diann Rusch-Feja), Hungarian (Laszlo Kovacs),
and Portuguese (Jose Borbinha).  I know of translations of DC-Simple into
Finnish, Swedish, Norwegian, and Danish, and I know there is interest
in French.  Most recently, I had a strong expression of interest for a
DC in Tibetan for use by monks scanning manuscripts for a repository of
Buddhist texts on the Web.

Who out there is interested in participating in this experiment?  Alpha
users willing to help solve the technical problems are especially welcome.

Cheers,
Tom

