Charles,

You wrote:
>>Note that for Approach 1 to work, the URL in a namespace
>>definition must point to the switch file, not to a locale. For
>>robustness, each locale should also point to a locale switch file so
>>that if an editor is pointed to a locale file (by mistake) it can
>>recover.
>
>Yes.  I wonder if it would be best to make the namespace definition
>point to a file containing the language-independent parts of the
>schema *and* a pointer to a separate switch file.
>
>When I say "file" I mean of course "URI".  And "file containing..."
>means "URI which when dereferenced would return...".  It's just so
>much easier to think in terms of files.

There are two separate issues here: inheritance and URIs.

The ability to inherit definitions is a generally useful feature for
schemas. By inherit, I mean the ability to 'import' a schema definition
and over-ride specific productions within it to derive a new schema. It
allows you to say things like "The AusGILS schema is exactly the same
as Dublin Core with these additional one or two properties", or "The
French Dublin Core is exactly the same as Dublin Core, except the
human semantic information has been replaced with French text."

Importing and over-riding means that subsequent modifications to the
base schema are automatically propogated to the derived schemas. It also
makes explicit what has changed in the derived schema.

The disadvantage is that processing a derived schema requires the 
software to fetch multiple schema definition files. From experience I
know that fetching *one* schema file across the web noticeably slows
starting a metadata editor. Having to fetch several (possibly from
around the world) is not likely to be fast.

I would like to have inheritance, and plan to experiment with it (in
my copious free time :-), but whether it will be practical...

URIs. I was being quite deliberate in talking about files (i.e. URLs).
If URNs existed, we would not need a switch file. Instead we could
adopt the convention that derived schemas had URNs that were extensions
of the base schema.

For example, if the base URI was:

	urn://...location.../DublinCore

then the URI for the French version would be:

	urn://...location.../DublinCore/Fr-fr

The generation of the URN for the specific language version of Dublin
Core would be easy (and vice versa). Because URNs do not imply location,
there is no problem with decentralising management of the language
specific versions.

Even though URNs haven't taken off, taking this approach but with URLs
(or PURLs) might not be a bad thing. It is neat and clean, and leaves
open the chance that URNs might save us.

