I went through the RDF schema proposal, and the example for DC.
It means now it is very easy (standard) to write:

<rdf:RDF
     xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/TR/WD-rdf-syntax#"
     xmlns:rdfs="http://www.w3.org/TR/WD-rdf-schema#">

<rdf:Description ID="Title">
    <rdf:instanceOf
rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/TR/WD-rdf-syntax#PropertyType"/>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">Title</rdfs:label>        
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">
          The name given to the resource, usually by the Creator or Publisher.
    </rdfs:comment>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="fr">Titre</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="fr">
          Le nom donn  la ressource par le crateur ou l'auteur.
</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Description>

etc.

How ever putting the locale definition in the reference definition is not
what we want (see Charles Wicksteed and all.' mails). We wante local
definitions such as:

<rdf:RDF
     xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/TR/WD-rdf-syntax#"
     xmlns:rdfs="http://www.w3.org/TR/WD-rdf-schema#">
     xmlns:rdfs="http://purl.oclc.org/metadata/dublin_core">

<rdf:Description about="http://purl.oclc.org/metadata/dublin_core#Title">
     <rdfs:label xml:lang="fr"> Titre </rdfs:label>
     <rdfs:comment xml:lang="fr">
          Le nom donn  la ressource par le crateur ou l'auteur.   
     </rdfs:comment>
</rdf:Description>

etc..

And use a switch file to select the various locale descriptions as Approach
1 in Charles's mail.

I hope RDF schemas allows for extending schema this way, since we do not
need (nor want) to use RDFS:subClassOf  here.

What do you think?

Anne-Marie

