On Thu, May 20, 1999 at 07:00:00PM +0700, Thomas Baker wrote:
> 	5. As defined in the RFC for Unqualified Dublin Core [RFC],
> 	Dublin Core elements consist of a descriptive name (eg, "Author
> 	or Creator"), a single-word label or "token" for use in encoding
> 	schemes (eg, "Creator"), and element definitions. The descriptive
> 	names and element definitions are meant to be read primarily
> 	by humans, the tokens primarily by machines. The tokens look
> 	like English words but stand for universal elements. Universal
> 	elements can have interchangeable names and definitions in
> 	multiple languages.

The tokens must:

    Be easily parsed by machines.

    Unambiguously refer to a specific concept.

    Be unambiguously and easily associated with other tokens that
    express the same concept.

Ideally, only one token is used to express a specific concept, or, at
least, there is an obvious correspondence.  But this cannot be
universally enforced, and there will always be exceptions.

Thus, the tokens must be expressed in a way that are unique,
intuitive, and unambiguous.

Tokens that have only a local concept (e.g. application specific) can
even be expressed in the local language, or in a non standard way.

In such standards, we are only interested in tokens with a universal
concept (that is they need to interoperate with other tokens,
universally, like in most applications today).  Such tokens, must be
expressed in a universal way.  This can be numbers, widely accepted
words (in this field), commonly used notation, etc.  We cannot limit
the ways that this is expressed, as long as it looks reasonable for a
world wide standard.

