>From the meeting in GMD, I was insisting on expressing this the other
way: the token must be defined "in a universally accepted way".

Anyway, the real issue was to make the token description independent
from the language in use.  This is needed to achive interoperability.
This is what a standard must say.  The standard must not specify
further decisions, that are a matter of policy.

English tokens are easier to read than numeric or random ones, but
have other disadvantages: there may be misspellings, some words may
have many meanings or writings, which may be confusing to the human
user, and reasons for errors (instead of providing readability).
Also, numeric tokens may be easier and more unambiguous to derive from
specific cases of data (e.g. Z39.50 databases).
But this is not an issue we have to resolve here.
This is a policy issue.

We should just not reject a set of policies, just because we cannot
see the reasons that someone may have to use them.  We can encourage
the use of "english language tokens", explaining the reasons, but we
should not try to enforce this, as this gives no technological
benefit.

sarantos

