Charles,

> The question is how we construct schemas for DC suitable
> for use by people from anywhere in the world.  The
> single-word label obviously does not change.  The full
> name of the element, its description, and any other helpful
> text needs to be translated.  We need to decide how this
> should be packaged so that the user gets presented with
> the right version, but the versions must still be easy to
> maintain.

Multi-lingual schemas were an important design goal when I commenced to
write a general purpose metadata editor for DSTC (this eventually became
Reggie).

My design goals for a multilingual schema were:

1)	Metadata should be presented in the language of the viewer
	irrespective of the language of the schema. For example, if I
	create a Dublin Core instance using the French schema, a German
	viewer should see the descriptive information in German.

2)	You should be able to create new translations *without*
	modifying the original schema. Otherwise someone has to
	continually modify the default schema as new translations are
	created; a maintenance nightmare.

Unfortunately, I haven't been able to come up with a clean solution that
satisfies both solutions.

My preferred approach is your Approach 1 (i.e. separate files for each
locale with a locale switch file). Separate files were implemented
both in Reggie and PrismEd (a side effect of having configurable
schemas!), but I never got around to implementing the locale switch
file. Note that for Approach 1 to work, the URL in a namespace
definition must point to the switch file, not to a locale. For
robustness, each locale should also point to a locale switch file so
that if an editor is pointed to a locale file (by mistake) it can
recover.

In other words the locale switch file would have...
<RDF:Description ID="DCSelection">
  <XXX:LocaleOption>
    <RDF:Description>
      <XXX:Locale>fr</XXX:Locale>
      <XXX:DefFile>elements_fr.rdf</XXX:DefFile>
    </RDF:Description>
  </XXX:LocaleOption>
  (etc)

and the french schema would have...

<RDF:Description ID="SchemaInfo">
  <XXX:LocaleSwitch><blah>/DublinCore/SwitchFile.rdf</XXX:LocaleSwitch>
  <XXX:ThisLocale>fr</XXX:ThisLocale>
</RDF:Description>
(etc)

You claim of Approach 2 (i.e. mixing the locales together in one file)
> The data (i.e. schema) is easier to manage, because you don't have to
> worry about putting it in separate files.  It could be stored in a
> database.

I disagree; I believe that Approach 2 makes it *harder* to manage the
various locale information because only *one* organisation is able to
manage the schema information. That one organisation has to manage
everything: from the default schema to the Ethopian Dublin Core schema.
Approach 1 allows the management to be decentralised.

For completeness, you also need to specify what schema properties can be
expressed in different languages. In Reggie and PrismEd there are two
"HCI" properties:
*	Label. This is a short (often one word) description intended
	to label buttons etc.
*	Description. This is a longer textual description intended for
	'help' screens. This text was marked up in HTML and was pointed
	to by a URL from the schema.

So in the English DC schema you have a file which contains...

	dublinCore attribute
        	description <http://(etc)/English/schema.html>
        	label 'Dublin Core'
        	container attribute set of
                	title, creator, subject, description, publisher,
                	contributors, date, type, format, source,
                	language, relation, coverage, rights

	title attribute
		description <http://(etc)/English/title.html>
		label 'Title'
		string string

and in the French DC schema you have a file which contains...

	dublinCore attribute
        	description <http://(etc)/French/schema.html>
        	label 'Dublin Core'
        	container attribute set of
                	title, creator, subject, description, publisher,
                	contributors, date, type, format, source,
                	language, relation, coverage, rights

	title attribute
		description <http://(etc)/French/title.html>
		label 'Titre'
		syntax string

