On Wed, Oct 20, 2004 at 09:35:05PM +0100, Andy Powell wrote:
> Do we have a policy about what happens to the old JISCMail list archives
> and so on when a WG closes down like this?

This is one of the main issues I had in mind when I raised
the issue of "archival policy" for DCMI in Shanghai.
My understanding of the current situation is as follows:

-- I am told that all DC-* lists on JISCMAIL were set up,
   at creation, to remain archived indefinitely (but not 
   necessarily accessible).

-- According to JISCMAIL policy, lists are deleted if not
   used over many years; i.e. dc-datamodel was last used in
   October 2000.  However, JISCMAIL holds the archives 
   indefinitely "for anyone wishing to obtain a copy or even 
   reinstate the list".

-- As a general rule, once a list has been deleted, access
   to the archives is stopped.  However, it is my
   understanding that JISCMAIL can continue to provide
   access on request.  At any rate, several deactivated
   DC- lists do remain accessible on JISCMAIL, such as
   http://www.jiscmail.ac.uk/lists/dc-schemas.html.

-- On the other hand, there are cases where links to
   deactivated working groups were broken and a substitute
   archive was set up on the DCMI Web site.  Two examples are:

       http://dublincore.org/groups/format/
       http://dublincore.org/groups/implementors/

-- Each of the two DCMI archives cited
   above includes a ZIP file of postings that is archived by
   DCMI.  The ZIP file for DC-FORMAT, for example, unpacks to:

    - 2000-11-21  14:56:06       3287  dc-format.log0002     
    - 2000-11-21  14:56:06       2356  dc-format.log0010     
    - 2000-11-21  14:56:06       2569  dc-format.log9901     
    - 2000-11-21  14:56:06     124608  dc-format.log9902     
    - 2000-11-21  14:56:06      67811  dc-format.log9903     
    - 2000-11-21  14:56:06       1515  dc-format.log9904     
    - 2000-11-21  14:56:06       8983  dc-format.log9905     
    - 2000-11-21  14:56:06      14928  dc-format.log9907     
    - 2000-11-21  14:56:06      15573  dc-format.log9908     
    - 2000-11-21  14:56:06      46085  dc-format.log9909     
    - 2000-11-21  14:56:06       9989  dc-format.log9910     
    - 2000-11-21  14:56:06      40757  dc-format.log9911     
    - 2000-11-21  14:56:06       8791  dc-format.log9912     

   It should be noted that the format of these files appears
   somewhat broken -- original mbox headers stripped, control
   characters inserted here and there, etc.  They cannot be
   loaded and threaded by generic, mbox-aware mail software
   (or by any mail software at all, as far as I can tell).

-- The Directorate has discussed this issue in the past,
   concluding that under the circumstances, our practical
   approach should perhaps be to request the archive in Zipped
   form for all deactivated groups.

-- In its first years, DCMI used MAILBASE, an excellent
   mailing list service that was at some point replaced by the
   less expensive JISCMAIL.  I had understood that JISCMAIL
   would continue to keep the MAILBASE archive accessible --
   and until recently it has been accessible -- but I am
   appalled now to discover that links such as

        http://www.mailbase.ac.uk/lists/dc-usage/2000-02/0059.html

   no longer resolve!  This is in my opinion a very serious
   issue, because the references cited in countless postings
   and working documents will no longer be accessible.  (To be
   more precise, the postings may still be accessible in some
   form because -- in my understanding -- old MAILBASE postings
   were folded into JISCMAIL at the time of transition,
   but now they would only be accessible through JISCMAIL
   browsing or queries, and there is no way to associate an
   old MAILBASE URL with a specific JISCMAIL posting).

-- I also have serious reservations about the long-term
   usability of JISCMAIL URIs such as:

       http://www.jiscmail.ac.uk/cgi-bin/wa.exe?A2=ind0106&L=dc-usage&O=D&P=8824

   I am assuming that such URIs rely on real-time database
   query resolution and are not maintained for persistence
   independently of those databases.  It bothers me that one 
   unique posting can be cited with

      http://www.jiscmail.ac.uk/cgi-bin/webadmin?A2=ind0406&L=dc-usage&P=R5684&D=0&H=0&I=-1&O=T&T=0
      http://www.jiscmail.ac.uk/cgi-bin/webadmin?A2=ind0406&L=dc-usage&T=0&F=&S=&P=5018

   and who knows how many other possible URIs.

DCMI is surely not the only organization or activity to have
this problem.  Given the importance of these email archives
to higher education -- and especially given the role now of
JISC in the UK affiliate of DCMI -- I should think that JISC
itself would have an interest in helping to resolve these
long-term issues.

In sum, it looks like the bits of mailing lists are being
preserved (some at JISCMAIL and some at DCMI), but access is
patchy, ad-hoc, and of dubious persistence.

Tom

