Dear WG chairs,

Hi... I recently took over from Paul Miller the administration of the
Jiscmail mailing lists used by DCMI WGs.

Makx has pointed out to me recently that the configuration of the WG
lists varies considerably, and has asked me to rationalise that. I've
already made a few adjustments where access settings were leaving lists
open to spam.

I'm proposing to make some changes to the configuration of the lists
supporting the following groups:

DCMI Accessibility Working Group
DCMI Agents Working Group
DCMI Architecture Working Group
DCMI Citation Working Group
DCMI Collection Description Working Group
DCMI Date Working Group
DCMI Education Working Group
DCMI Environment Working Group
DCMI Global Corporate Circle
DCMI Government Working Group
DCMI Kernel/ERC Working Group
DCMI Libraries Working Group
DCMI Localization and Internationalization Working Group
DCMI Persistent Identifier Working Group
DCMI Preservation Working Group
DCMI Registry Working Group
DCMI Standards Working Group
DCMI Tools Working Group
DCMI Type Working Group
DCMI User Documentation Working Group

1. List-ownership, notifications and error messages
===================================================
For some WG lists, I am currently the only list-owner. This means that
I'm the only person who can make alterations to the list configuration.

It also means that any messages sent to the
dc-xxxxx-request@jiscmail.ac.uk address, rather than to the list, will
be seen only by me. Now often these messages do relate only to the
mechanics of the list and I'm happy to deal with them, but often they
relate to the business of the WG and are best dealt with by WG chairs.

I'm proposing to make all current WG chairs co-list-owners of their WG
lists so that (a) they all see this email and (b) they all have the
authority to alter the list configuration.

There are a further two classes of message that need to be handled.
These are generated by the Jiscmail server.

(a) error messages (usually when the server finds that the email address
of a subscriber is unreachable, either temporarily or permanently
because e.g. they've changed job and forgotten to unsubscribe from the
list)

(b) notifications of subscription/unsubscription (every time someone
joins/leaves the list)

In an effort to make sure WG chairs do get the information they needd
but don't receive error messages they don't know how to act on, I'm
proposing to set the configurations so that
- the error messages are sent to me but _not_ to the WG chairs
- the subscription/unsubscription messages are sent both to me and to
the WG chairs

This means that WG chairs will (start to or continue to) see messages
from the Jiscmail server when people subscribe/unsubscribe from the
list, but these are informational only (except in the few cases of lists
which are intentionally closed). And you will also receive the mail sent
directly to the list-owner address. But you will not get the error
messages.

If on the other hand, you _do_ want to receive the error messages as
well, let me know and I can set that accordingly.

Similarly, if you do _not_ want to receive notifications, let me know
and I can set that accordingly.


2. Subscription/Review options
==============================
I'm proposing to change the subscription options for the above lists so
that they are all set to

Subscription=Open, Confirm

i.e. open to user subscription, subject to that user responding to a
confirmation email from the server. i.e. subscribers do _not_ require
the approval of list-owners to subscribe to a WG list.

(N.B. this is only for the WG lists above, which should be open for
people to join. Other lists are closed/controlled for whatever reason
and I'll leave that as it is.)

I'm proposing to change the review options for the above lists so that
they are all set to

Review=Private

This means that only people subscribed to the lists can obtain a list of
subscribers.

There is also a good deal of variation in whether the the server sets a
Reply-To list or Reply-To sender header. But I'm hesitant to alter those
on the basis that existing list members are probably accustomed to the
existing behaviour.

If I don't hear from you, I'll assume this is OK ;-) And I'll implement
the changes suggested above for the lists above on Wednesday 10 March
2004.

